title: Tell stories to go far
description: Every once in a while, you'll be given the opportunity to tell a story that will change your trajectory.
categories: think-different
---

Every single day, you're given a chance to put on whichever disguise you choose. Every single day, you have the choice to unveil the story of yourself. The better you are at telling stories, the further you'll go. You'll climb to impossible places. You'll float on the clouds. You'll be able to sell your boss on the big raise, hire the big client, or even woo *her* to be your wife.

I don't operate that way though.

My modus operandi is simple: *do &mdash; every &mdash; single &mdash; day.* Because I don't spend time telling the story of what I *do*, I undoubtedly leave vast amounts of potential opportunities on the table.

I'm okay with that, but...

Perhaps once every year or two, an occasion arises where the chance to tell a story becomes irresistible. This usually comes in a high-stakes situation where the possible outcome is life-changing. It could be a large business deal, new job prospect, investment opportunity, or other potential life-impact event. I take a lot of time drafting, formatting, drafting, formatting, and fine-tuning so that the story is unveiled *just right*. So far, this effort has never disappointed me; it has always yielded massive payoffs.

Story-telling is not about lying or masking truth. It's about unveiling truth in the most convincing way possible. It's deciding "what is important to tell" and "when to tell it."

In the business world, so much time is spent building feature after feature, product after product &mdash; and nobody ever hears about it. Put bluntly, *more* time should be spent storytelling than building.

As a matter of fact, there are plenty of examples that exist *only* as stories.

<img class="float-left h-48 mr-4 mb-4" alt="Diamond Shreddies" src="data:image/jpeg;base64,">

Take the quintessential example: Shreddies.

Back in the 1990s, Shreddies, known as the square-shaped wheat cereal, was phasing out of popularity. In an attempt to draw back consumers, they released one of the greatest marketing campaigns of all time by a simple 45º rotation: Diamond Shreddies.
